-- U.S. Gulf Coast Crudes Weaken After Valero Shuts Texas Unit
-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 2012-04-02T17:45:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-02/u-s-gulf-coast-crudes-weaken-after-valero-shuts-texas-unit.html
U.S. Gulf Coast oil premiums to West
 Texas  Intermediate weakened after  Valero Energy Corp. (VLO)  shut a
fluid catalytic cracker for maintenance at its McKee refinery in
Texas for planned work.  Maintenance on the 55,000-barrel-a-day gasoline unit is
scheduled to last about five weeks, the company said earlier
this year. Work at Exxon Mobil Corp.’s Baytown refinery in
Texas, which idled a similar unit at the beginning of February
for planned repairs, is still in progress, according to Patricia Errico, a company spokeswoman.  Light Louisiana Sweet’s (USCSLLSS)  premium to May WTI lost $1.15 to
$21.25 a barrel over the U.S. benchmark at 11:01 a.m. in  New
York , according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Heavy Louisiana
Sweet (USCSHLSE) ’s premium decreased 65 cents to $22.90 a barrel.  Thunder Horse ’s premium widened 60 cents to $18.60 a barrel
over WTI, and  Mars Blend (USCSMARS)  lost 30 cents to a premium of $15.35.
Poseidon’s premium decreased 50 cents to $14.35, while Southern
Green Canyon’s added 30 cents to $15.30.  West Texas Sour (USCSWTSM) ’s discount widened $1.20 a barrel to $7.35
below WTI.  Western Canada Select (USCSWCAS) ’s discount narrowed 50 cents to
$23.50 a barrel. Bakken oil’s was steady at $11 a barrel, and
Syncrude’s discount was unchanged at $4.25.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Aaron Clark in New York at 
